rature is placed in a wider context through a consideration of what British writing reached the USA, and vice versa, and also through an exploration of wartime Europe as it was shown to British children. Questions of leadership, authority, individualism, community, conformity, urban-rural division, ageism, class, race, and gender awareness are explored. In this incredibly broad-ranging book, covering over 100 writers, Owen Dudley Edwards looks at the literary inheritance when the war broke out and asks whether children's literary diet was altered in the war temporarily or permanently. Concerned with the effects of the war as a whole on what children could read during the war and what they made of it, he reveals the implications of this for the world they would come to inhabit.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChildrenxBooks and readingxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aChildrenxBooks and readingzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectsxGreat BritainxGreat BritainxVerenigd Koninkrijk van Groot-Brittannië en Noord-IerlandxEnglisch. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748628728zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748628728423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748628728/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA1